hese women in their ability to be daring advocates for gender equality. She shows how a number of these women were linked through the generations by their memberships in activist women’s organizations.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFeminism and mass mediaxHistoryxCanada. 0aFeminism and mass mediazCanadaxHistory. 0aWomen in the mass media industryxHistoryxCanada. 0aWomen in the mass media industryzCanadaxHistory. 0aWomen journalistsxHistoryx19th centuryxCanada. 0aWomen journalistsxHistoryx20th centuryxCanada. 0aWomen journalistszCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen journalistszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 0aWomen's rightsxHistoryx19th centuryxCanada. 0aWomen's rightsxHistoryx20th centuryxCanadaxCanada. 0aWomen's rightszCanadaxHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen's rightszCanadaxHistoryy20th century. 4aFilm & Media. 4aPolitical Science. 4aSocial Science: Women’s Studies. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Media Studies.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010z978311127414008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010z978311127721940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781554583133423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781554583133/original  a978-3-11-127414-0  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2011-2010c2010d2011  a978-3-11-127721-9  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package 2011 - 2010c2010d2011  aGBV-deGruyter-alles